README.md
     1‚Üí# debug
     7‚ÜíA tiny JavaScript debugging utility modelled after Node.js core's debugging
     8‚Üítechnique. Works in Node.js and web browsers.
     9‚Üí
    10‚Üí## Installation
    12‚Üí```bash
    13‚Üí$ npm install debug
    14‚Üí```
    15‚Üí
    16‚Üí## Usage
    18‚Üí`debug` exposes a function; simply pass this function the name of your module, and it will return a decorated version of `console.error` for you to pass debug statements to. This will allow you to toggle the debug output for different parts of your module as well as the module as a whole.
    19‚Üí
    20‚ÜíExample [_app.js_](./examples/node/app.js):
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí```js
    23‚Üívar debug = require('debug')('http')
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    73‚Üí#### Windows command prompt notes
    75‚Üí##### CMD
    77‚ÜíOn Windows the environment variable is set using the `set` command.
    78‚Üí
    79‚Üí```cmd
    80‚Üíset DEBUG=*,-not_this
    81‚Üí```
    82‚Üí
    83‚ÜíExample:
    84‚Üí
    85‚Üí```cmd
    86‚Üíset DEBUG=* & node app.js
    87‚Üí```
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üí##### PowerShell (VS Code default)
    91‚ÜíPowerShell uses different syntax to set environment variables.
    92‚Üí
    93‚Üí```cmd
    94‚Üí$env:DEBUG = "*,-not_this"
    95‚Üí```
    96‚Üí
    97‚ÜíExample:
    98‚Üí
    99‚Üí```cmd
   100‚Üí$env:DEBUG='app';node app.js
   101‚Üí```
   102‚Üí
   103‚ÜíThen, run the program to be debugged as usual.
   104‚Üí
   105‚Üínpm script example:
   106‚Üí```js
   107‚Üí  "windowsDebug": "@powershell -Command $env:DEBUG='*';node app.js",
   108‚Üí```
   109‚Üí
   110‚Üí## Namespace Colors
   112‚ÜíEvery debug instance has a color generated for it based on its namespace name.
   113‚ÜíThis helps when visually parsing the debug output to identify which debug instance
   114‚Üía debug line belongs to.
   115‚Üí
   116‚Üí#### Node.js
   118‚ÜíIn Node.js, colors are enabled when stderr is a TTY. You also _should_ install
   119‚Üíthe [`supports-color`](https://npmjs.org/supports-color) module alongside debug,
   120‚Üíotherwise debug will only use a small handful of basic colors.
   121‚Üí
   122‚Üí<img width="521" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/71256/29092181-47f6a9e6-7c3a-11e7-9a14-1928d8a711cd.png">
   123‚Üí
   124‚Üí#### Web Browser
   126‚ÜíColors are also enabled on "Web Inspectors" that understand the `%c` formatting
   127‚Üíoption. These are WebKit web inspectors, Firefox ([since version
   128‚Üí31](https://hacks.mozilla.org/2014/05/editable-box-model-multiple-selection-sublime-text-keys-much-more-firefox-developer-tools-episode-31/))
   129‚Üíand the Firebug plugin for Firefox (any version).
   130‚Üí
   131‚Üí<img width="524" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/71256/29092033-b65f9f2e-7c39-11e7-8e32-f6f0d8e865c1.png">
   132‚Üí
   133‚Üí
   134‚Üí## Millisecond diff
   136‚ÜíWhen actively developing an application it can be useful to see when the time spent between one `debug()` call and the next. Suppose for example you invoke `debug()` before requesting a resource, and after as well, the "+NNNms" will show you how much time was spent between calls.
   137‚Üí
   138‚Üí<img width="647" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/71256/29091486-fa38524c-7c37-11e7-895f-e7ec8e1039b6.png">
   139‚Üí
   140‚ÜíWhen stdout is not a TTY, `Date#toISOString()` is used, making it more useful for logging the debug information as shown below:
   141‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   145‚Üí## Conventions
   147‚ÜíIf you're using this in one or more of your libraries, you _should_ use the name of your library so that developers may toggle debugging as desired without guessing names. If you have more than one debuggers you _should_ prefix them with your library name and use ":" to separate features. For example "bodyParser" from Connect would then be "connect:bodyParser".  If you append a "*" to the end of your name, it will always be enabled regardless of the setting of the DEBUG environment variable.  You can then use it for normal output as well as debug output.
   148‚Üí
   149‚Üí## Wildcards
   151‚ÜíThe `*` character may be used as a wildcard. Suppose for example your library has
   152‚Üídebuggers named "connect:bodyParser", "connect:compress", "connect:session",
   153‚Üíinstead of listing all three with
   154‚Üí`DEBUG=connect:bodyParser,connect:compress,connect:session`, you may simply do
   155‚Üí`DEBUG=connect:*`, or to run everything using this module simply use `DEBUG=*`.
   156‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   161‚Üí## Environment Variables
   163‚ÜíWhen running through Node.js, you can set a few environment variables that will
   164‚Üíchange the behavior of the debug logging:
   165‚Üí
   166‚Üí| Name      | Purpose                                         |
   167‚Üí|-----------|-------------------------------------------------|
   168‚Üí| `DEBUG`   | Enables/disables specific debugging namespaces. |
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   181‚Üí## Formatters
   183‚ÜíDebug uses [printf-style](https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Printf_format_string) formatting.
   184‚ÜíBelow are the officially supported formatters:
   185‚Üí
   186‚Üí| Formatter | Representation |
   187‚Üí|-----------|----------------|
   188‚Üí| `%O`      | Pretty-print an Object on multiple lines. |
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   196‚Üí### Custom formatters
   198‚ÜíYou can add custom formatters by extending the `debug.formatters` object.
   199‚ÜíFor example, if you wanted to add support for rendering a Buffer as hex with
   200‚Üí`%h`, you could do something like:
   201‚Üí
   202‚Üí```js
   203‚Üíconst createDebug = require('debug')
   204‚ÜícreateDebug.formatters.h = (v) => {
   205‚Üí  return v.toString('hex')
   206‚Üí}
   207‚Üí
   208‚Üí// ‚Ä¶elsewhere
   209‚Üíconst debug = createDebug('foo')
   210‚Üídebug('this is hex: %h', new Buffer('hello world'))
   211‚Üí//   foo this is hex: 68656c6c6f20776f726c6421 +0ms
   212‚Üí```
   213‚Üí
   214‚Üí
   215‚Üí## Browser Support
   217‚ÜíYou can build a browser-ready script using [browserify](https://github.com/substack/node-browserify),
   218‚Üíor just use the [browserify-as-a-service](https://wzrd.in/) [build](https://wzrd.in/standalone/debug@latest),
   219‚Üíif you don't want to build it yourself.
   220‚Üí
   221‚ÜíDebug's enable state is currently persisted by `localStorage`.
   222‚ÜíConsider the situation shown below where you have `worker:a` and `worker:b`,
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   248‚Üí## Output streams
   250‚Üí  By default `debug` will log to stderr, however this can be configured per-namespace by overriding the `log` method:
   251‚Üí
   252‚ÜíExample [_stdout.js_](./examples/node/stdout.js):
   253‚Üí
   254‚Üí```js
   255‚Üívar debug = require('debug');
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   274‚Üí## Extend
   275‚ÜíYou can simply extend debugger 
   276‚Üí```js
   277‚Üíconst log = require('debug')('auth');
   278‚Üí
   279‚Üí//creates new debug instance with extended namespace
   280‚Üíconst logSign = log.extend('sign');
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   288‚Üí## Set dynamically
   290‚ÜíYou can also enable debug dynamically by calling the `enable()` method :
   291‚Üí
   292‚Üí```js
   293‚Üílet debug = require('debug');
   294‚Üí
   295‚Üíconsole.log(1, debug.enabled('test'));
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   341‚Üí## Checking whether a debug target is enabled
   343‚ÜíAfter you've created a debug instance, you can determine whether or not it is
   344‚Üíenabled by checking the `enabled` property:
   345‚Üí
   346‚Üí```javascript
   347‚Üíconst debug = require('debug')('http');
   348‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   357‚Üí## Usage in child processes
   359‚ÜíDue to the way `debug` detects if the output is a TTY or not, colors are not shown in child processes when `stderr` is piped. A solution is to pass the `DEBUG_COLORS=1` environment variable to the child process.  
   360‚ÜíFor example:
   361‚Üí
   362‚Üí```javascript
   363‚Üíworker = fork(WORKER_WRAP_PATH, [workerPath], {
   364‚Üí  stdio: [
